12/19/22, 10:00 - Kanishka Garg _GG: Location- 5 :- Dainimara
Latitude- 21.479515 N
Longitude- 86.75767 E

This location showed us the whole process of weathering from bed rock to soil. The soil layers had huge boulders known as "Core stones" which might have been formed due to seepage of chemical weathering agent through the fractures and joint planes.

The country rock of the region is Singhbhum Granite which can be identified by its constituent minerals which are Hornblende (dark coloured), K-Feldspar and Quartz. These minerals are identified on the basis of color, lustre and cleavage planes.

It is fine grained and discoloured due to weathering. In weathered part of Singhbhum Granite feldspar changes to kaolinite, biotite changes to chlorite whereas quartz which is more resistant develops some fractures. Soil is present as the uppermost layer, below soil lies weatherd rock and the fresh rocks are present at the bottom. Fresh rocks are the rocks which are not discoloured, had no weathering and erosion.
  The section which we observed has soil as its uppermost part followed by weatherd rocks and core stone at the base.The soil was of red colour which was formed from weathering of the granite for a long time. The next layer, most weatherd rocks, went under a lot of physical and chemical weathering. They were mostly reddish in colour due to oxidation of iron and were very soft and can be easily broken off by a hammer. The last layer was that of core stone, which had a little of no weathering , had joints in it and were very hard to break. Fresh rocks were not visible on the surface.

12/20/22, 19:03 - Kanishka Garg _GG: Location- 4:- Trildi

Latitude- 21.505846 N
Longitude- 81.704326 E

The region had Trildi laterite, which is both a soil and a rock type rich in iron and aluminium. Nearly all laterites are of rusty-red coloration, because of high iron oxide content. It contains secondary minerals such as limonite, goethite,lepidocrocite, greenalite and some small amount of haematite.
Laterites are formed from the tropical weathering (laterization), which is a prolonged process of chemical weathering, and leaching of parent sedimentary rocks (sandstones, clays, limestones); metamorphic rocks (schists, gneisses, migmatites); igneous rocks (granites, basalts, gabbros, peridotites); and mineralized proto-ores;which leaves the more insoluble ions, predominantly iron and aluminum.  
Surfaces present in the region had a pillow like structure and the other showing capillary structure with distinct transition between the two. An essential feature for the formation of laterite is the repetition of wet and dry seasons. Rocks are leached by percolating rain water during the wet season; the resulting solution containing the leached ions is brought to the surface by capillary action during the dry season.

Alternate red and black layered pattern was observed on the vertical cross sections of the site .The black layer are in direct contact with rainfall protecting other layers.
The inner surface might be more weathered because of water seepage through capillaries that acts like tunnels.The upper layer of the soil is hard while the lower layer is soft. Also, the upper layer is vesicular but the lower layer is having fine grained particles due to percolation of water.
12/20/22, 19:05 - Sharansh vardhan RK GG +0: Location 3 send kar
12/20/22, 19:05 - Sharansh vardhan RK GG +0: O
12/20/22, 19:12 - Kanishka Garg _GG: Location -3 :- Bhalukasauni

Latitude- 21.479986N
Longitude- 86.692219E

This location is about 10 kms south of Bhalukasuni Village .It is also known as Ambojorah locally. The location was an active mining site with rocks having blue surface because of the active mining. Most of the rocks were a part of igneous Dolerite, having parallel cooling joints which were formed together in Singhbhum Granite. 
              The rocks in this region are younger than the country rock because this is a dyke that cross-cut the pre-existing country rock.The dyke is fine grained, dark coloured. The minerals in it (plagioclase) has sub-vitreous lustre. Hence, the dyke is identified to be dolerite.The rocks showed distinct joint sets, which are parallel and very closely spaced.Most of the rock mass is the dolerite dyke.
               The two types of rocks present in the region have compositional differences as the Granite contains more amount of alkali feldspar than plagioclase feldspar whereas the amount of plagioclase feldspar is greater than alkali feldspar in diorite.

12/21/22, 10:16 - Kanishka Garg _GG: Location 6 : Panchalingheswar

Latitude- 21.411337N
Longitude- 86.729679E

The location was 827 meters above sea level and the rock at this location was a very special type of Singhbhum Granite which is
Granophyre and it is one of the hardest forms of rock. Quartz, Feldspar and Plagioclase Feldspar were the main minerals which were found in the rocks at this site. Feldspar present at this location are very fine and they are interlocked with Quartz. Cracks and joints were rarely seen in rocks at this location and they are so tight that rain also can't break them in 2.5 Billion years. The amount of weathering in the rocks was very less.

No cooling joints were observed in rocks of the location and the dikes here have weathered out. 

Vegetation through cracks and joints were observed as water can flow through them.
12/21/22, 10:16 - Kanishka Garg _GG: Location- 5 :- Dainimara
Latitude- 21.479515 N
Longitude- 86.75767 E

This location showed us the whole process of weathering from bed rock to soil. The soil layers had huge boulders known as "Core stones" which might have been formed due to seepage of chemical weathering agent through the fractures and joint planes.

The country rock of the region is Singhbhum Granite which can be identified by its constituent minerals which are Hornblende (dark coloured), K-Feldspar and Quartz. These minerals are identified on the basis of color, lustre and cleavage planes.

It is fine grained and discoloured due to weathering. In weathered part of Singhbhum Granite feldspar changes to kaolinite, biotite changes to chlorite whereas quartz which is more resistant develops some fractures. Soil is present as the uppermost layer, below soil lies weatherd rock and the fresh rocks are present at the bottom. Fresh rocks are the rocks which are not discoloured, had no weathering and erosion.
  The section which we observed has soil as its uppermost part followed by weatherd rocks and core stone at the base.The soil was of red colour which was formed from weathering of the granite for a long time. The next layer, most weatherd rocks, went under a lot of physical and chemical weathering. They were mostly reddish in colour due to oxidation of iron and were very soft and can be easily broken off by a hammer. The last layer was that of core stone, which had a little of no weathering , had joints in it and were very hard to break. Fresh rocks were not visible on the surface.
12/21/22, 10:16 - Kanishka Garg _GG: Location-1: NILAGIRI

Latitude- 21.46505 N
Longitude- 86.766721 E 

Location 1 had Singhbhum granite which is 3.8 billion years old. Considerable amounts of vegetation and light colored minerals were observed in the Nilagiri region.The light coloured minerals in the rocks were mainly identified to be Quartz, Plagioclase Feldspar, Muscovite, Orthoclase Feldspar.

The rocks present at the location were dipping in some direction with different dip values. The repetition of such rocks represents joints.

Moreover distinct joint sets were observed in the rocks i.e. fractures dividing the rocks into two sections that have not moved away from each other. They occur in distinct sets and are distinguished from fractures and fault planes.
Joints are formed due to the crystallization of  magma beneath the surface of the earth, some parallel isothermal planes subnormal to which the stresses are maximum puts the either side of rock apart to form Joints. Joints control the stability of rock because the magma while crystallizing separates into different rock along joint planes. 

According to our overall observation the rocks were mostly weathered due to exposure to air, water and other physical conditions and most of the rocks present at location 1 were hard and massive with distinct sets with moderate joint spacing.
12/21/22, 10:16 - Kanishka Garg _GG: Location-2 - MIRGUNI (Kata Pahad)

Latitude- 21.450591° N

Longitude- 86.65757 °E

Location 2 was Kata Pahad which is a 3 billion years old Granitic outcrop called Nilgiri Granite, where newer dolerite dykes intruded through Singhbhum Granite basement, Hornblende Granite. The region was a mining site which also had a deep water reservoir, formed due to mining activities. The rocks were hard and massive and the Country rock of the region was granite with more content of Hornblende in it that's why it was named Hornblende Granites.

There were two types of rocks in the region 
Country Rock (Hornblende Granites) consisting Quartz, Plagioclase Feldspar, Hornblende and Orthoclase Feldspar) and Dolerite Dykes (Comprising Dolerites).

Silica Veins are found in most of the rocks. It mainly comprises Quartz. Quartz settles in the fractures of the rocks hence forming the quartz Veins.

Although dykes were Plutonic igneous rocks which were formed beneath the surface, they came up to the surface mainly due to land upliftment and weathering.

The Basement Rocks appeared to have gneissic traces over them. It is due to instantaneous release of pressure over the rocks thus forming foliations over them.

Exfoliation surfaces were observed in the granite which happened due to diurnal temperature difference. This happens in granite because it is hard and the temperature variation between different layers is significant and grains are very fine.

4/10/23, 08:27 - Vasu Verma GG: Quartz for hyperpycnal flow.


Vasu Verma
Calculate the concentration of quartz sediment necessary to make the river water as hyperpycnal flow. Consider seawater density (1003 kg/m3), density of the Quartz sediment 2650 kg/m3,

To make river water into hyperpycnal flow, the sediment concentration needs to be high enough to make the mixture denser than seawater.

The density of seawater is 1003 kg/m3. For the river water to become hyperpycnal, the density of the mixture needs to exceed 1003 kg/m3.

The density of Quartz sediment is 2650 kg/m3.

Let's assume that we have a certain volume of river water, say 1 cubic meter, and we want to calculate how much Quartz sediment we need to add to reach hyperpycnal flow.

Let's use the variable "x" to represent the concentration of Quartz sediment in kg/m3.

The density of the mixture can be calculated using the following formula:

Density of Mixture = (Volume of River Water x Density of River Water + Volume of Quartz Sediment x Density of Quartz Sediment) / (Volume of River Water + Volume of Quartz Sediment)

We know that the volume of river water is 1 cubic meter. Let's assume we want to add enough Quartz sediment to make the mixture 10% sediment by volume.

That means the volume of Quartz sediment we need to add is 0.1 cubic meters.

Plugging in the numbers:

Density of Mixture = (1 m3 x 1000 kg/m3 + 0.1 m3 x 2650 kg/m3) / (1 m3 + 0.1 m3)
Density of Mixture = (1000 kg + 265 kg) / 1.1 m3
Density of Mixture = 1181.8 kg/m3

Since 1181.8 kg/m3 is greater than the density of seawater (1003 kg/m3), the mixture will be hyperpycnal.

So to make river water as hyperpycnal flow, we would need to add Quartz sediment at a concentration of at least 265 kg/m3 (assuming a starting river water density of 1000 kg/m3).

4/10/23, 08:30 - Shaurya_😎: Quartz Sediment Concentration.


Shaurya
Calculate the concentration of quartz sediment necessary to make the river water as hyperpycnal flow. Consider seawater density (1003 kg/m3), density of the Quartz sediment 2650 kg/m3,

Hyperpycnal flow occurs when the sediment concentration in a water body exceeds the critical concentration, which is the minimum concentration required for the sediment-laden flow to sink and flow along the bottom. To calculate the concentration of quartz sediment necessary to make the river water as hyperpycnal flow, we need to determine the critical concentration.

The critical concentration can be calculated using the following equation:

Cc = (ρs - ρw) / (ρs - ρc)

Where:
Cc = critical concentration
ρs = density of sediment (2650 kg/m3 for quartz sediment)
ρw = density of water (1003 kg/m3 for seawater)
ρc = density of the suspended sediment particles

Assuming the density of suspended sediment particles is 2650 kg/m3 (same as quartz sediment), we can calculate the critical concentration as follows:

Cc = (2650 - 1003) / (2650 - 2650) = 0.609

Therefore, the critical concentration for quartz sediment in seawater is 0.609.

To make the river water as hyperpycnal flow, the concentration of quartz sediment must exceed the critical concentration. Therefore, the concentration of quartz sediment required to make the river water as hyperpycnal flow is:

Cs > Cc
Cs > 0.609

In other words, the concentration of quartz sediment must be greater than 0.609 for the river water to become hyperpycnal flow.

4/10/23, 08:49 - Shaurya_😎: Quartz Sediment Concentration.


Shaurya
Calculate the concentration of quartz sediment necessary to make the river water as hyperpycnal flow. Consider seawater density (1003 kg/m3), density of the Quartz sediment 2650 kg/m3,

Hyperpycnal flow occurs when the sediment concentration in a water body exceeds the critical concentration, which is the minimum concentration required for the sediment-laden flow to sink and flow along the bottom. To calculate the concentration of quartz sediment necessary to make the river water as hyperpycnal flow, we need to determine the critical concentration.

The critical concentration can be calculated using the following equation:

Cc = (ρs - ρw) / (ρs - ρc)

Where:
Cc = critical concentration
ρs = density of sediment (2650 kg/m3 for quartz sediment)
ρw = density of water (1003 kg/m3 for seawater)
ρc = density of the suspended sediment particles

Assuming the density of suspended sediment particles is 2650 kg/m3 (same as quartz sediment), we can calculate the critical concentration as follows:

Cc = (2650 - 1003) / (2650 - 2650) = 0.609

Therefore, the critical concentration for quartz sediment in seawater is 0.609.

To make the river water as hyperpycnal flow, the concentration of quartz sediment must exceed the critical concentration. Therefore, the concentration of quartz sediment required to make the river water as hyperpycnal flow is:

Cs > Cc
Cs > 0.609

In other words, the concentration of quartz sediment must be greater than 0.609 for the river water to become hyperpycnal flow.




Shaurya
On a hillslope with a weathering rate of 20 mm/yr and an effective hillslope diffusivity of 0.02m2/yr, what would be the expected curvature of the hillslope? Consider equilibrium or steady state between weathering and hillslope process. Suppose in the same hillslope

The curvature of a hillslope refers to its shape and is related to the balance between erosion and weathering. At equilibrium or steady-state conditions, the rate of weathering is equal to the rate of hillslope transport. In this case, the expected curvature of the hillslope can be estimated using the following equation:

R = D/W

where R is the radius of curvature, D is the effective hillslope diffusivity, and W is the weathering rate.

Substituting the given values into the equation, we get:

R = 0.02 m2/yr / 0.02 cm/yr
R = 100 cm = 1 m

Therefore, the expected radius of curvature of the hillslope is 1 m.

It is important to note that this is a simplified estimate based on idealized assumptions, and actual hillslopes may exhibit greater variability in curvature due to variations in material properties, climate, and other factors.

4/14/23, 13:24 - Shaurya_😎: 1.Open the feedback form of ERP.
2. Click on the subject code and the professor button.
3. Open console in browser.
   To do that, press F12 for firefox, press Ctrl + Shift + J in Chrome.
4. Copy the code in paste in that console window and hit Enter.
5. All fields would be filled by now (If not refresh 2-3 times and try again).
6. Fill up the captcha and submit.

try{
  var x = myframe.document.querySelectorAll('textarea');
  var i = 0;
  for (i = 0; i < x.length; i++){
    x[i].value="NIL";
  }

  x = myframe.document.querySelectorAll('input[type="radio"]');
  for (i = 1; i < x.length; i++){
      if (x[i].getAttribute('name') == 'check'){
          continue;
      }
      x[i].click();
  }

}catch(err){
  console.log(err);
}
